\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The path of the trade balance?
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TB_{t}=y_{t}-c
\]

\end_inset

It follows that in “good times” (i.e., when 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is high), the economy will run trade surpluses, while in “bad times” (i.e.,
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}$
\end_inset

 is low) the economy will run trade deficits.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Current account (Saving): 
\begin_inset Formula $CA_{t}=rb_{t}+y_{t}-c_{t}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
When output switches from high to low, the current account balance worsens
 since consumption is ﬂat and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a predetermined variable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, in bad times, the economy increases its borrowing from the rest of
 the world.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stationary Equilibrium (I)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Concept is identical to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

steady state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If exogenous variables are constant over time, so will endogenous variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}=y^{H}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $c=r\left(b_{0}+\int_{0}^{\infty}y_{t}e^{-rt}dt\right)=rb_{0}+y^{H}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Trade balance 
\begin_inset Formula $TB_{t}=y^{H}-\left(rb_{0}+y^{H}\right)=-rb_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stationary Equilibrium (II)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In a stationary equilibrium, the Current account (=saving = 
\begin_inset Formula $rb_{t}+y_{t}-c_{t}$
\end_inset

) will always be zero.
 Why?
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{b_{t}}=rb_{t}+y_{t}-c_{t}=rb_{t}-rb_{0}
\]

\end_inset

At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{b}_{0}=rb_{t}-rb_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}=b_{0}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since net foreign assets 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}$
\end_inset

 are constant over time, the current account is always zero along a stationary
 equilibrium.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center} 
\backslash
Huge How Shocks affect the economy
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Welfare Analysis
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We conclude that the economy adjusts immediately to a permanent negative
 shock.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 falls immediately, the trade balance 
\begin_inset Formula $TB_{t}=y^{L}-c^{L}=-rb_{0}$
\end_inset

 does not change.
 Current account 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{b_{t}}=rb_{t}+y_{t}-c_{t}=rb_{0}-rb_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 also does not change.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since there are no distortions in this economy, this response is socially
 optimal.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
This result underlies the standard policy prescription that says that, however
 painful, an economy has no choice but to adjust to any long-lasting negative
 shock.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unanticipated Shocks: Temporary Fall in Output
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
There is an unanticipated and temporary fall in output.
 Formally, the path of output for 
\begin_inset Formula $t≥0$
\end_inset

.
 Precisely speaking 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y & =y^{L},\;0\leq t<T\\
y & =y^{H},\;t\geq T
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The budget constraint becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{\infty}c_{t}e^{-rt}dt=b_{0}+\int_{0}^{T}y^{L}e^{-rt}dt+\int_{T}^{\infty}y^{H}e^{-rt}dt
\]

\end_inset

The equilibrium condition implies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c=rb_{0}+y^{L}\left(1-e^{-rT}\right)+y^{H}e^{-rT}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unanticipated Shocks—mathematics 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Given 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
c & =rb_{0}+y^{L}\left(1-e^{-rT}\right)+y^{H}e^{-rT}\tag{1.30}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then trade balance are constants
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
TB_{t} & =y^{L}-c=-rb_{0}-\left(y^{H}-y^{L}\right)e^{-rT}<-rb_{0}\;t<T\\
TB_{t} & =y^{H}-c=-rb_{0}+\left(y^{H}-y^{L}\right)\left(1-e^{-rT}\right)>-rb_{0}\;t>T
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The saving (current account)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\dot{b} & =rb_{t}+y^{L}-c,\;t<T\\
\dot{b} & =rb_{t}+y^{H}-c,\;t>T
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Use the formula of first order DE, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b_{t} & =b_{0}e^{rt}+\frac{y^{L}-c}{r}\left(e^{rt}-1\right),\;t<T\\
b_{t} & =b_{T}e^{r(t-T)}+\frac{y^{H}-c}{r}\left(e^{r\left(t-T\right)}-1\right),\;t>T
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unanticipated Shocks—mathematics
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{t}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
b_{t} & =b_{0}-e^{-r\left(T-t\right)}\left(\frac{y^{H}-y^{L}}{r}\right)\left(1-e^{rt}\right)\;t<T\\
b_{t} & =b_{0}-\left(\frac{y^{H}-y^{L}}{r}\right)\left(1-e^{rT}\right)\;t\geq T
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Take the first derivative
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{b}_{t} & =-\left(y^{H}-y^{L}\right)e^{-r\left(T-t\right)}<0\;t<T\label{eq:bdot}\\
\dot{b}_{t} & =0\;t\geq T\label{eq:bdotp}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unanticipated Shocks—the response of current account
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The second derivate provide information on how CA (saving) changes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{b_{t}}=-r\left(y^{H}-y^{L}\right)e^{-r\left(T-r\right)}<0\label{eq:bdoubledot}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{b}_{0}=rb_{0}+y^{L}-c<0$
\end_inset

.
 We know when the shock happens, the current account drops.
 
\end_layout

