\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
In a stochastic version of our model, this comovement would translate into
 a positive correlation between saving and output.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The average correlation is positive in both group of countries (in fact
 the correlation is negative in only two out of the 40 countries, both developin
g).
 Further, the average correlation is smaller in developing (0.46) than in
 industrial countries (0.79).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Conclusion
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
In a world with no frictions and a constant world real interest rate, a
 small open economy will achieve perfect consumption smoothing even when
 output fluctuates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The key message that follows from the analysis of unanticipated negative
 shocks is that the economy “adjusts” to permanent shocks but “finances”
 temporary shocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In practice, however, many countries face a variety of frictions that will
 imply substantial (and welfare-reducing) departures from this first-best
 world.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator parbreak
\end_inset


